[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{FULLCHAPTERNAME}}]]

{{cheese}}
[[Image:Red Leicester.jpg|right|thumb|Red Leicester cheese]]

'''Red Leicester''' is an orange coloured cow's milk cheese, originally from Leicestershire in England. It has a firm texture, which makes it suitable for grating, and it is a good choice for use in [[Cookbook:Cheese on Toast|cheese on toast]] or with a baked [[Cookbook:Potato|potato]]. At its best, it has a slightly nutty taste.

{{recipe}}
'''Cheese on toast''' - a simple concept but easy to get wrong. Thick cut [[Cookbook:Bread|bread]] is your first requirement. Toast one side of it under a medium [[Cookbook:Grilling|grill]] (called a broiler in some regions of the world). While it's browning, grate some cheese. You need a firm fleshed, strong flavoured cheese. Lightly toast the other side of the bread, just enough to warm it, then spread the grated cheese over it. You can add pickles, finely chopped onion, or even some crushed walnuts at this stage. Grill (broil) the cheesy side of the bread until the cheese is bubbling and brown. Eat quickly, but be careful, as the cheese will be tongue-burningly hot!
[[Category:Sandwich recipes]] [[Category:Cheese recipes]] [[Category:Broiled recipes]] [[Category:Grilled recipes]]

This stage involves using the NADH molecules produced previously, along with electrons from reduced electron carriers, to from molecules of ATP.  In eukaryotes this process takes place in the mitochondria, while in oxygen tolerant prokaryotes it takes place in the cell membrane.  Some eukaryotic cells, such as red blood cells, do not have mitochondria and therefore cannot use the electron transport chain to produce energy.

In plant cells, energy is used from the sun to start chemical reactions which create ATP.

