{{Japanese todo| # Negative conjugation # Expand on habitual and stative verbs. }}
The ～ている form has several uses. * Progressive * Completed actions * Stative * Habitual * Incomplete actions
== Conjugation == While Japanese grammar doesn't always correspond to what we know from English, they both use auxiliary verbs in many circumstances.
Continuous tenses in English use the auxiliary verbs '''am''', '''are''', '''is''', '''was''' and '''were'''.
{| class="wikitable" ! past/non-past Tense !! Continuous past/non-past tense |- |I ride the train. |I am riding the train. |- | I rode the train. | I was riding the train. |- |He talks to a friend. |He is talking to a friend. |- | He talked to a friend. | He was talking to a friend. |}
The Japanese language has a similar auxiliary verb '''いる''' with the ～て form of the verb.
{| class="wikitable" |+ '''Politeness of the 〜て form''' ! colspan="1" | !! Non-past tense !! Past Tense |- ! Polite | +います || +いました |- ! Plain | +いる || +いた |}
== Uses ==
=== Continuous Actions === {{wikipedia|Continuous and progressive aspects}} When speaking of continuous actions that occur in the present or occurred in the past, the form has the same meaning as the English continuous tense.
{| class="wikitable" |+ '''Examples''' ! colspan="2" | past/non-past tense ! rowspan="2" | English |- ! Plain || Polite |- | テレビを{{furi|見|み|ている}}。 | テレビを{{furi|見|み|ています}}。 | I am watching television. |- | {{furi|音楽|おんがく}}を{{furi|聞|き|いている}}。 | {{furi|音楽|おんがく}}を{{furi|聞|き|いています}}。 | I am listening to music. |- | {{furi|雑誌|ざっし}}を{{furi|読|よ|んでいる}}。 | {{furi|雑誌|ざっし}}を{{furi|読|よ|んでいます}}。 | I am reading a magazine. |- | {{furi|宿題|しゅくだい}}をしていた。 | {{furi|宿題|しゅくだい}}をしていました。 | I was doing my homework. |- | {{furi|友達|ともだち}}と{{furi|食|た|べていた}}。 | {{furi|友達|ともだち}}と{{furi|食|た|べていました}}。 | I was eating with a friend. |}
=== Incomplete tasks ===
When you take the present-negative conjugation of いる, you're left with a sense an action not taking place.
{| class="wikitable" |+ '''Examples''' ! colspan="2" | past/non-past tense ! rowspan="2" | English |- ! Plain || Polite |- | テストの{{furi|勉強|べんきょう}}をしていない || テストの{{furi|勉強|べんきょう}}をしていません|| I haven't done any studying for the test. |- |{{furi|宿題|しゅくだい}}をしていない | まだ{{furi|宿題|しゅくだい}}をしていません | I haven't done the homework yet. |}
=== Habitual ===
This form may also be used to describe a habitual activity.
{| {{Japanese example}} | style="padding-left: 2em; width: 50%;" | USAトゥデーの新聞を読んでいます。 | I read the USA Today newspaper. |}
=== Stative vs Non-stative verbs === Much like English, there are verbs that describe a state of the subject, rather than an action. These type of verbs are called [[w:stative verbs|stative verbs]]. You may want to think of these as actions that started in the past, arrived to a state, and this state persists to the present.
{| {{Japanese example}} | style="padding-left: 2em; width: 50%;" | 図書館は今、開いています。 | The library is open. |}
=== くる, いく, and かえる === When the verbs くる, いく, and かえる are used in the ～て in conjuction with the auxiliary verb いる, they're translated as '''has come''', '''has gone''', and '''has returned''', respectively.
== Exceptions ==
There are some irregular cases with this form.
# You can use the word 知っています, but not 知っていません. Instead, you'll use the negative form of masu - 知りません. # You also can't use ある, いる, and 要る in the ～ている form at all. The same can be said with potential forms of verbs (e.g., 話せる).
== Colloquial Variations == When speaking at a high speed, sometimes syllables are dropped from words to make them easier to say. Colloquial variations of the continuous forms exist and are recognized in the Japanese language. While they are not used in proper writing, these forms are used in every day conversation, especially among friends and family.
{| class="wikitable" ! colspan="1" | !! Standard !! Colloquial variation |- ! Plain | {{furi|電車|でんしゃ}}に{{furi|乗|の|っている}} | {{furi|電車|でんしゃ}}に{{furi|乗|の|ってる}} |- ! Polite | {{furi|電車|でなしゃ}}に{{furi|乗|の|っています}} | {{furi|電車|でんしゃ}}に{{furi|乗|の|ってます}} |}
All the sentences mean "I am riding the train." Notice that the two sentences on the right have simply dropped the い from いる／います. By dropping the い, the sentence becomes easier to say quickly. This is a standard colloquial form of the continuous tense, and it works with the non-past continuous and the past continuous. The above example is the present continuous, so let's see an example of the past continuous:
{| class="wikitable" ! colspan="1" | !! Standard !! Colloquial variation |- ! Plain | {{furi|妹|いもうと}}と{{furi|遊|あそ|んでいた}} | {{furi|妹|いもうと}}と{{furi|遊|あそ|んでた}} |- ! Polite | {{furi|妹|いもうと}}と{{furi|遊|あそ|んでいました}} | {{furi|妹|いもうと}}と{{furi|遊|あそ|んでました}} |}
Once again, the い was dropped, which forms the colloquial variation. Just remember to use the standard form when writing, but when speaking, the colloquial version will be OK when speaking among friends. However, when speaking to someone of higher status, you may wish to use the standard polite form.
